{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487494","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487494"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:12:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"359"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582596"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:48:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:48:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"359"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/359"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.11,0.47,0.18,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105980"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/359"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88455"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"354"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16985"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105980"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-year history of difficulty swallowing. Initially she noticed pieces of meat getting stuck, but now finds that even liquids can cause problems. Her difficulties are worse at night when she wakes with a choking feeling and liquid dribbling from her mouth. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has not lost any weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Physical examination is unremarkable apart from obesity with a BMI of 31 kg/m\u00b2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oesophageal carcinoma","Peptic stricture","Achalasia","Pharyngeal pouch","Para-oesophageal hiatus hernia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a three-year history of progressive dysphagia to both solids and liquids, associated with nocturnal regurgitation. The long duration of symptoms, absence of weight loss, and characteristic nocturnal symptoms strongly suggest achalasia. In achalasia, failure of the lower oesophageal sphincter to relax and loss of oesophageal peristalsis lead to progressive dilatation of the oesophagus. When patients lie flat, accumulated food and liquid regurgitate, causing the nocturnal choking episodes described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAchalasia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the slowly progressive dysphagia to both solids and liquids over three years, nocturnal regurgitation, and absence of weight loss. While relatively rare (incidence of three per 100,000 per year), this presentation is classic for the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with more rapid progression of symptoms (weeks to months rather than years), dysphagia initially to solids only, and significant weight loss. The three-year duration makes malignancy highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic stricture\u003C/strong\u003E results from chronic gastro-oesophageal reflux disease and would typically present with a history of heartburn and dysphagia predominantly to solids. The absence of reflux symptoms and the dysphagia to liquids make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a sensation of food sticking in the throat, gurgling sounds in the neck, and regurgitation of undigested food particles hours after eating. Patients often describe having to cough to expel retained material from the pouch. The pattern of symptoms in this case is not consistent with a pharyngeal pouch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPara-oesophageal hiatus hernia\u003C/strong\u003E may cause dysphagia and postprandial symptoms but would not typically cause the progressive dysphagia to liquids or the characteristic nocturnal regurgitation seen in this patient. Most hiatus hernias are asymptomatic or cause reflux symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Achalasia is characterised by slowly progressive dysphagia to both solids and liquids, often with nocturnal regurgitation.","The long duration of symptoms (years) and absence of weight loss help distinguish achalasia from oesophageal malignancy.","Nocturnal regurgitation occurs in achalasia due to spillover from a dilated, aperistaltic oesophagus when lying flat."],"references":["Patel DA, Lappas BM, Vaezi MF. An Overview of Achalasia and Its Subtypes. Gastroenterology \u0026 Hepatology. 2017; 13:411-21. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5572971/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88455"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"359"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88455","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88455"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-15T16:49:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-15T16:49:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"359"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105980"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/354"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Achalasia","synonym